1.2 Voxel world model
Think of the world as a set of voxel volumes.

Each volume may represent:

asteroid field body

ship hull body

station hull/interior body

terrain tile

ruin volume

salvage wreck section

Each volume is divided into chunks.

Recommended chunk responsibilities
Each chunk should own:

voxel density / occupancy

voxel material IDs

damage state data

local flags

dirty state

mesh state

collision state

connectivity metadata

compression/serialization data

1.3 Recommended voxel cell data
Do not store giant bloated structs unless needed. Use compact data.

A practical voxel can logically contain:

material ID

solidity / fill

damage state

flags

Example conceptual voxel fields
struct FVoxelCell
{
    uint16 MaterialId;
    uint8 Fill;          // 0 = empty, 255 = full
    uint8 Damage;        // intact/cracked/burned/etc
    uint8 Flags;         // airtight, conductive, structural, reserved
};
You may later split this into separate arrays for cache efficiency.

1.4 Chunk size
A good starting point is something like:

16×16×16 if you want simpler updates

32×32×32 if you want fewer chunk objects and better large-scale throughput

For your project, I would start with:

32×32×32 chunks
and test aggressively.

That usually gives a good balance for:

ships

stations

asteroids

salvage chunks

